      <hedline>
        <hl1>Moms and Dads, at Work and at Home</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>National Parenting Association pres Ruth A Wooden letter holds that rising number of dual-income parents could be powerful sleeper issue in future elections0</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Now a Majority: Families With 2 Parents Who Work'' (news article, Oct. 24):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Now a Majority: Families With 2 Parents Who Work'' (news article, Oct. 24):</p>
        <p>What effect will the rise in dual-income parents have on the elections? Our recent nationwide survey found that working parents say balancing job and family is their biggest daily challenge. It's not surprising that mothers say this, but fathers say so, too, and to the same extent, 32 percent.</p>
        <p>This could be a powerful sleeper issue in this and future elections. Among undecided parent voters in our sample, 39 percent pointed to work-family balance as their top challenge. While both presidential candidates have focused much attention on family concerns like education, they have largely missed this huge issue.</p>
        <p>RUTH A. WOODEN  President  National Parenting Association  New York, Oct. 24, 2000</p>
      </block>
